Accordingly, it took as the main objective of the work the revision of the assessment of the importance of services in international trade and a new determination of their share. The consequence of such a formulated objective was the adoption of three research hypotheses, namely:
- the reason for the discrepancy between the dominant importance of the service sector in the economies of the countries and the relatively low share of services in the economic flows of these countries is the underestimation of the turnover of international trade in services, which is related to the way it is defined and the measurement methodology that results from the definition adopted;
- the way international trade in services is captured, as adopted in the General Agreement on Trade in Services (GATS), does not exhaust all forms of their cross-border provision;
- the way international trade in services is measured on the basis of balance of payments statistics results in a significant underestimation.
